BUSINESS CONTEXT(Write a description of the business context):

EMPATHY MAP:
For this you must write what the user will likely 'say', 'think', 'does' and 'feels'. How does user in essence react and
how we can understand and empathesise with them.

Example: 
  User 'says': I need more information before visting the zoo.
  User 'Thinks': I wish there was a website where I could see all the animals, it would be easy to decide if 
                  I want to go this zoo.
  User 'Does': Comes to the zoo with very little awareness. Comes to visit, but the zoo is too full today.
  User 'Feels': 'Overwhelmed', 'confused', 'stressed and annoyed because the que of the ticket.'

USER STORIES:

Table Structure:
As a [user]...  |  I want...  |  so that...  |  Acceptable critera

example of the table:
As a [user]... = First time customer
As a [First time customer]

I want... To visit a website and find some information on what the zoo is offering

So that... I can compare it with other zoos and see why I chose this one, as well as that I would be able to see if
there are animals that I am particularly interested in. I will not have to wait in the que for tickets, when I visit.

Acceptance Criteria: The system should allow user to see the clear navigation bar at the top, in the main section there 
should be a carousel in the main section that will prompt users to all the other sections. When user visits the about page,
all of the necessary info will be displayed in there such as how to get here, opening times, animals, facilities, hotel info.
On the top right corner there will be "book" button that will prompt page, it could be a ticker booking or a hotel booking.

Analysis:
I want... section is esentially saying what the user wants.

So that... section is saying what he can do with that want or why they want it.

The acceptance criteria section describes the expected outcomes that must be met for the user’s problem 
to be considered solved.
